⚖️ LCES: Legal Calculus Educational System

🟦 The Three Core Roles of LCES

LCES separates legal workflow into three distinct functional roles.

Why?

Because many procedural failures happen when planning, drafting, and testing are blended together without discipline.

LCES creates role clarity:

🧩 Architect

✍️ Builder

🛡️ Inspector

Each has a separate responsibility, separate outputs, and clear boundaries.

🔹 1. Architect — Structural Logic

Primary responsibility:

- Issue framing

• Procedural sequencing

• Workflow design

• Missing-information mapping

• Scope definition

Key outputs:

- Blueprint for next steps

• Filing sequence

• Required components checklist

• Structural plan

Functional boundary:

✅ Builds the blueprint

❌ Does not draft full prose

❌ Does not red-team the work product

The Architect decides what must exist before writing begins.

🔹 2. Builder — Transformation

Primary responsibility:

- Convert structure into usable prose

• Assemble supported drafts

• Translate logic into work product

Key outputs:

- Draft filings

• Notices

• Declarations

• Factual summaries

• Proposed orders

Functional boundary:

✅ Converts structure into text

❌ Does not redesign the framework

❌ Does not add unsupported strategy

The Builder turns planning into language.

🔹 3. Inspector — Adversarial Testing

Primary responsibility:

- Stress-test the draft

• Identify defects before filing

• Detect review risks

Key outputs:

- Weakness detection

• Gap identification

• Contradiction flags

• Preservation analysis

• Structural vulnerability reports

Functional boundary:

✅ Tests survivability under scrutiny

❌ Does not rewrite the document

❌ Does not give legal advice

The Inspector asks:

Would this survive the court?

Would this survive opposing counsel?

🟨 The core insight:

When one person tries to architect, build, and inspect simultaneously, blind spots multiply.

LCES separates the functions so the work becomes clearer, stronger, and more defensible.

⚖️ Structure first.

Text second.

Testing third.

